PHASE 1 — Networking Fundamentals: Complete Notes
Lesson 1.1 — What is a Daemon?
The word "daemon" comes from Greek mythology — a spirit that operated in the background, doing work without being seen. In Unix/Linux, this meaning carried over perfectly.
A daemon is a program that:

Runs in the background
Has no controlling terminal (no keyboard, no screen attached)
Starts at boot time (usually)
Waits silently for something to happen (a connection, a file change, a timer)
Responds automatically when triggered

Real Examples of Daemons:
DaemonWhat It DoessshdWaits for SSH connections on port 22httpd / nginxWaits for web requests on port 80/443cronWaits for a scheduled time, then runs jobssystemdManages all other daemonsbluetoothdManages Bluetooth connectionssyslogdCollects and stores system log messages
NORMAL PROGRAM (like ls, python script):
─────────────────────────────────────────
  You run it → It does its job → It exits
  [terminal] → [program] → [done]


DAEMON:
─────────────────────────────────────────
  System boots
       │
       ▼
  [daemon starts] ──► detaches from terminal
       │
       ▼
  [runs silently in background]
       │
       ▼
  ┌────────────────────────────┐
  │   EVENT LOOP (infinite)    │
  │                            │
  │  waiting...waiting...      │
  │  ← CONNECTION ARRIVES →   │
  │  handle it                 │
  │  waiting...waiting...      │
  │  ← ANOTHER CONNECTION →   │
  │  handle it                 │
  │  ...forever...             │
  └────────────────────────────┘
       │
       ▼
  Only stops when:
  - admin kills it (kill, systemctl stop)
  - system shuts down

Lesson 1.2 — Process vs Daemon vs Service vs Server
Process:

A process is a running program with its own memory space, PID (Process ID), and CPU time.
┌──────────────────────────────────────────┐
│              PROCESS                     │
│                                          │
│  PID: 4821                               │
│  Memory: [code][stack][heap][data]       │
│  State: running / sleeping / zombie      │
│  Owner: your username                    │
│  Parent: the process that launched it    │
└──────────────────────────────────────────┘
Daemon vs Process:
PROCESS                        DAEMON
────────────────               ────────────────────────
Has a terminal    ──vs──       No terminal (detached)
Runs once                      Runs forever (event loop)
User launches it               System/init launches it
Dies when done                 Dies only when killed
Service:

A service is a daemon managed by the init system (like systemd).
DAEMON (raw concept):
  "A background process"

SERVICE (managed daemon):
  "A daemon that systemd knows about,
   can start/stop/restart/monitor automatically"

  systemctl start nginx    ← managing a service
  systemctl status sshd    ← checking a service
All services are daemons. Not all daemons are formally registered as services.
Server (in networking context):
  CLIENT                          SERVER
  ──────                          ──────
  Makes requests      ──────►     Listens for requests
  Initiates contact               Waits passively
  Connects TO server              Accepts connections
  Example: your browser           Example: nginx, our daemon
Full Picture:
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                   YOUR MACHINE                      │
│                                                     │
│  ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────┐  │
│  │              systemd (init system)            │  │
│  │  manages ──► registers ──► monitors           │  │
│  └──────────────┬───────────────────────────────┘  │
│                 │                                   │
│         ┌───────┴────────┐                         │
│         │                │                         │
│    ┌────▼─────┐    ┌─────▼────┐                   │
│    │  sshd    │    │  nginx   │  ← daemons/        │
│    │ (daemon) │    │ (daemon) │    services/        │
│    │ (service)│    │ (service)│    servers          │
│    │ (server) │    │ (server) │                    │
│    └──────────┘    └──────────┘                    │
│                                                     │
