Lesson 1.3 — TCP vs UDP
TCP = Certified mail. UDP = Dropping a postcard in a mailbox.
TCP — Transmission Control Protocol:

Guaranteed delivery (lost packets are resent)
Ordered (packets arrive in sequence)
Integrity checked (checksums)
Flow controlled (sender doesn't overwhelm receiver)
Cost: overhead

TCP DATA FLOW:
──────────────────────────────────────────────
Sender                              Receiver
  │                                    │
  │─── packet 1 ──────────────────────►│ ✓
  │─── packet 2 ──────────────────────►│ ✓
  │─── packet 3 ──────────(LOST)───────│ ✗
  │◄── "please resend 3" ──────────────│
  │─── packet 3 ──────────────────────►│ ✓
  │─── packet 4 ──────────────────────►│ ✓
                                        │
                             Delivers to app
                             in order: 1,2,3,4
Used for: Web browsing (HTTP/HTTPS), SSH, email, file transfer, our daemon.
UDP — User Datagram Protocol:

Connectionless (no setup)
Unreliable (packets may be lost, duplicated, or out of order)
Fast (no overhead, no waiting for acknowledgments)

UDP DATA FLOW:
──────────────────────────────────────────────
Sender                              Receiver
  │                                    │
  │─── packet 1 ──────────────────────►│ ✓
  │─── packet 2 ──────────(LOST)───────│
  │─── packet 3 ──────────────────────►│ ✓
  │─── packet 4 ──────────────────────►│ ✓
                                        │
                             Delivers to app:
                             1, 3, 4 (2 gone forever)
                             No complaints, no retry
Used for: Video streaming, DNS, online games, VoIP.
Comparison Table:
┌─────────────────┬──────────────────┬──────────────────┐
│   Property      │      TCP         │      UDP         │
├─────────────────┼──────────────────┼──────────────────┤
│ Connection      │ Required first   │ None needed      │
│ Reliability     │ Guaranteed       │ Not guaranteed   │
│ Order           │ Maintained       │ Not maintained   │
│ Speed           │ Slower (overhead)│ Faster           │
│ Use case        │ Accuracy matters │ Speed matters    │
│ Header size     │ 20-60 bytes      │ 8 bytes          │
│ Examples        │ HTTP, SSH, SMTP  │ DNS, VoIP, games │
└─────────────────┴──────────────────┴──────────────────┘
Our daemon uses TCP — because we're building a chat/command server where losing messages is unacceptable.

Lesson 1.4 — IP Addresses
An IP address is the unique identifier for a device on a network — like a postal address for your computer.
IPv4 — 32 bits, written as 4 numbers (0–255) separated by dots:
192  .  168  .   1   .  100
───     ───     ───     ───
 8 bits  8 bits  8 bits  8 bits
              = 32 bits total
         = ~4.3 billion addresses
Special IP Addresses:
┌──────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────────┐
│ Address          │ Meaning                              │
├──────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┤
│ 127.0.0.1        │ Loopback — "this machine itself"     │
│ localhost        │ Same as 127.0.0.1 (hostname alias)  │
│ 0.0.0.0          │ "All interfaces on this machine"     │
│ 192.168.x.x      │ Private home/office network          │
│ 10.x.x.x         │ Private corporate network            │
│ 8.8.8.8          │ Google's public DNS server           │
└──────────────────┴──────────────────────────────────────┘
Why 0.0.0.0 matters for our daemon:
YOUR SERVER MACHINE
───────────────────
  Interface: eth0 → 192.168.1.50  (local network)
  Interface: eth1 → 10.0.0.5      (another network)
  Interface: lo   → 127.0.0.1     (loopback)

Bind to 127.0.0.1    → only local programs can connect
Bind to 192.168.1.50 → only that one network
Bind to 0.0.0.0      → ALL of the above simultaneously

Lesson 1.5 — Ports
An IP address gets you to a machine. A port gets you to a specific program on that machine.

IP address = apartment building address
Port = apartment number inside the building

INCOMING PACKET ARRIVES AT YOUR MACHINE
────────────────────────────────────────
Destination: 192.168.1.50 : 80
                   │          │
                   │          └──► Port 80  → nginx (web server)
                   └─────────────► Your machine

Another packet:
Destination: 192.168.1.50 : 22
                              └──► Port 22  → sshd (SSH daemon)

Another:
Destination: 192.168.1.50 : 9000
                              └──► Port 9000 → OUR DAEMON
Port Ranges:
┌─────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ Range           │ Category                               │
├─────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ 0 – 1023        │ Well-known ports (need root to bind)  │
│                 │ HTTP=80, HTTPS=443, SSH=22, FTP=21     │
├─────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ 1024 – 49151    │ Registered ports (normal user can use)│
│                 │ Common for custom apps                 │
├─────────────────┼────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ 49152 – 65535   │ Ephemeral/dynamic ports               │
│                 │ OS assigns these to clients            │
└─────────────────┴────────────────────────────────────────┘
Our daemon will use port 9000.

Lesson 1.6 — Client-Server Architecture
CLIENT-SERVER MODEL
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  CLIENT                                    SERVER
  ──────                                    ──────
  (your terminal,                           (our daemon)
   chat app, etc.)

  1. Knows server's IP + port
  2. Initiates connection ──────────────►   3. Was already waiting
                                            4. Accepts connection
  5. Sends data (request) ─────────────►   6. Receives, processes
                          ◄─────────────   7. Sends response
  8. Receives response
  9. May send more...
  ... (conversation continues)
  10. Closes connection  ──────────────►   11. Cleans up, waits again

KEY INSIGHT:
  Server must be running BEFORE client tries to connect.
  Server is PASSIVE (waits).
  Client is ACTIVE (initiates).

Lesson 1.7 — The Socket Concept
A socket is the software abstraction that represents one endpoint of a network connection.

A phone call needs two phones.
A network connection needs two sockets — one on each end.

SOCKET — THE ENDPOINT ABSTRACTION
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  YOUR PROGRAM                         REMOTE PROGRAM
  ───────────                          ──────────────
  ┌─────────┐                          ┌─────────┐
  │         │                          │         │
  │  Your   │                          │ Remote  │
  │  Code   │                          │  Code   │
  │         │                          │         │
  └────┬────┘                          └────┬────┘
       │                                    │
  ┌────▼────┐    ════ NETWORK ════     ┌────▼────┐
  │ SOCKET  │◄──────────────────────►  │ SOCKET  │
  │ (file   │                          │ (file   │
  │ descri- │                          │ descri- │
  │  ptor)  │                          │  ptor)  │
  └─────────┘                          └─────────┘

A socket is identified by:
  (IP address, Port, Protocol)
  e.g. (192.168.1.50, 9000, TCP)

In Linux, a socket is just a FILE DESCRIPTOR.
Linux File Descriptor Table (per process):
  fd 0 → stdin  (keyboard)
  fd 1 → stdout (screen)
  fd 2 → stderr (screen, for errors)
  fd 3 → [a file you opened]
  fd 4 → [a SOCKET you created]   ← our socket lives here
  fd 5 → [another socket]

Lesson 1.8 — TCP Three-Way Handshake
Before any data flows over TCP, the two sides must establish a connection through the three-way handshake.
TCP THREE-WAY HANDSHAKE
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  CLIENT                                      SERVER
  ──────                                      ──────
  (wants to connect)                     (listening on port 9000)

  Step 1 — SYN:
  "I want to connect.                ──SYN──►
   My sequence number is X."

  Step 2 — SYN-ACK:
  "OK, I got your SYN.           ◄──SYN-ACK──
   My sequence number is Y.
   Acknowledging your X."

  Step 3 — ACK:
  "Got it. Acknowledging Y.          ──ACK──►
   Connection established!"

  ════ CONNECTION IS NOW OPEN — DATA CAN FLOW ════
TCP Flags:
┌──────┬────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│ Flag │ Meaning                                    │
├──────┼────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│ SYN  │ Synchronize — "I want to start a connection"│
│ ACK  │ Acknowledge — "I received what you sent"   │
│ FIN  │ Finish — "I want to close the connection"  │
│ RST  │ Reset — "Something went wrong, abort"      │
│ PSH  │ Push — "Deliver this to app immediately"   │
│ URG  │ Urgent — "Priority data"                   │
└──────┴────────────────────────────────────────────┘

Lesson 1.9 — How Linux Handles Sockets Internally
The Tea Stall Analogy
YOU  = your daemon (the tea stall owner)
CUSTOMERS = clients who want to connect
STEP 1: You SET UP your stall          → create socket
STEP 2: You PUT A SIGN "Open at 9000"  → bind to port 9000
STEP 3: You OPEN A WAITING LINE        → listen()
STEP 4: Customers JOIN THE LINE        → clients send SYN
STEP 5: You call "NEXT!" and serve     → accept()
The Two Queues Inside the Kernel
YOUR TEA STALL (the daemon)
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

                        PORT 9000
                           │
                           │  ← clients arrive here
                           ▼
        ┌──────────────────────────────────────┐
        │         QUEUE 1: SYN QUEUE           │
        │         (The "Checking" Line)         │
        │                                      │
        │  Client says: "Hello!" (SYN)         │
        │  Kernel replies: "Wait!" (SYN-ACK)   │
        │  Kernel waits for client's ACK       │
        │                                      │
        │  ┌──────┐ ┌──────┐ ┌──────┐         │
        │  │Cust A│ │Cust B│ │Cust C│         │
        │  │SYN   │ │SYN   │ │SYN   │         │
        │  │sent  │ │sent  │ │sent  │         │
        │  └──────┘ └──────┘ └──────┘         │
        └──────────────┬───────────────────────┘
                       │  handshake completes ✓
                       ▼
        ┌──────────────────────────────────────┐
        │         QUEUE 2: ACCEPT QUEUE        │
        │         (The "Ready to Serve" Line)   │
        │                                      │
        │  Fully handshaked, waiting for you   │
        │                                      │
        │  ┌──────┐ ┌──────┐                  │
        │  │Cust A│ │Cust B│                  │
        │  │READY │ │READY │                  │
        │  └──────┘ └──────┘                  │
        └──────────────┬───────────────────────┘
                       │  YOU call accept()
                       ▼
              ┌─────────────────┐
              │   YOUR DAEMON   │
              │  "Next please!" │
              │  Takes Cust A   │
              └─────────────────┘
Timeline of One Client Connecting
CLIENT MACHINE                        LINUX KERNEL (server side)
──────────────                        ──────────────────────────

1. Client sends SYN
                    ──── SYN ────►
                                      Kernel receives SYN.
                                      Puts client in SYN QUEUE.
                                      ┌─────────────┐
                                      │  SYN QUEUE  │
                                      │ [client X]  │ ← added
                                      └─────────────┘

2. Kernel auto-replies
                    ◄── SYN-ACK ──
                                      Still waiting for ACK.

3. Client sends ACK
                    ──── ACK ────►
                                      Handshake COMPLETE.
                                      REMOVES from SYN QUEUE.
                                      ADDS to ACCEPT QUEUE.
                                      ┌───────────────┐
                                      │ ACCEPT QUEUE  │
                                      │  [client X]   │ ← ready
                                      └───────────────┘

4. YOUR DAEMON calls accept()
                                      Kernel picks [client X].
                                      Hands you a NEW socket fd.

5. You talk to client X via new fd.
Two Sockets After accept()
BEFORE accept():
════════════════
  fd=4  ← LISTENING SOCKET
         "The front door. Never talks to
          clients directly. Only accepts entry."


AFTER accept():
════════════════
  fd=4  ← LISTENING SOCKET  (stays open, waits for MORE clients)
  fd=5  ← CLIENT SOCKET     (brand new, only for THIS one client)


WITH 3 CLIENTS:
════════════════
  fd=4  LISTENING SOCKET (stays open always)
         │
         ├── client 1 connects → accept() → fd=5
         ├── client 2 connects → accept() → fd=6
         └── client 3 connects → accept() → fd=7

  Talk to client 1 → through fd=5
  Talk to client 2 → through fd=6
  Talk to client 3 → through fd=7
  New clients still → through fd=4
The Backlog Number
listen(sock, backlog=3)

ACCEPT QUEUE can hold max 3 fully connected clients:

  ┌────────┬────────┬────────┐
  │client A│client B│client C│  ← FULL (3/3)
  └────────┴────────┴────────┘

  4th client tries to connect →
  Queue is FULL →
  Kernel sends RST →
  Client gets "Connection refused"

  If accept() is called quickly, slots free up for new clients.
